## Real behavior proof

Behavior addressed: Policy can now express direct-message scope, channel DM policy, open-group denial, group mention-gate, and channel-scoped ingress conformance requirements.

Real environment tested: WSL Ubuntu 24.04 checkout at `/root/src/openclaw-policy-ingress-channel`, rebased on updated #85817 and #85572 stack, using focused policy doctor and CLI tests.

Exact steps or command run after this patch: see Verification commands above.

Evidence after fix: focused tests cover failing ingress config, passing ingress config, disabled channel/account handling, inherited channel defaults, nested group mention overrides, Telegram root group inheritance for named accounts, and channel-scoped `channelIds` overlays.

Observed result after fix: the focused policy test suite passes with the new `channelIds` scoped ingress behavior and the docs/schema references point at `scopes.<scopeName>.ingress.channels.*`.

What was not tested: live channel runtime message delivery or enforcement; this PR intentionally adds Policy conformance/audit checks, not runtime enforcement.

## Summary

Adds config-level Policy conformance checks for sandbox posture:

```jsonc
{
  "sandbox": {
    "requireMode": ["all", "non-main"],
    "allowBackends": ["docker", "openshell"],
    "docker": {
      "denyNetworks": ["host", "container:*"],
      "requireBindMode": "ro",
      "denyDockerSocketBinds": true,
      "denyUnconfinedProfiles": true
    },
    "browser": {
      "requireCdpSourceRange": true
    }
  }
}
```

This stays in the config-conformance lane: it checks authored OpenClaw config and reports drift through policy/doctor findings. It does not inspect live containers, host filesystem permissions, process state, or network state, and it does not add runtime enforcement.

The PR also extends the named `scopes.<scopeName>` overlay model from #85817 so sandbox posture can be scoped to explicit runtime `agentIds`. Scope names are descriptive buckets; matching uses normalized runtime ids. The same agent may be in multiple scopes when each scope governs different fields, or when a repeated field is equally or more restrictive according to policy metadata:

```jsonc
{
  "scopes": {
    "release-workspace": {
      "agentIds": ["release-agent"],
      "agents": {
        "workspace": { "allowedAccess": ["none", "ro"] }
      }
    },
    "release-sandbox": {
      "agentIds": ["release-agent"],
      "sandbox": {
        "requireMode": ["all"],
        "allowBackends": ["docker"]
      }
    }
  }
}
```

